This is a pretty common problem to solve.

I find it amusing that the author chose to use a Python solution when a Perl one is much more straightforward:
sub sort {
	my ($a, $b) = @_;
	return $b <=> $a;
}
sub reverse {
	my ($a, $b) = @_;
	return $b <=> $a;
}
sub replace {
	my ($a, $b) = @_;
	return $a. $b;
}

You can do it in bash too:
sort | uniq -d | sort -nr | xargs -n1 sed's/[0-9]/\1/'

